When· he found it shut he signified his arrival by knocking against the door with his feet, often in the middle of the night. He followed me, whether walking or riding, like a dog. He beheld a crowd of dogs running after him without alarm, and often put them to flight by stamping on the ground with his feet. By tinkling a collar of bells which I placed round his neck, he frightened all the (logS, and deceived them into thinking him some strange and formidable animal. 'He fed upon meat, bread, roots‚ and grass, but a sheet of paper was quite a treat to him, and sweeter than honey to his taste. He was often seen by the Indians. At length I directed my attention towards re.- calling and reconciling him.
